</SPAN><BR><SPAN id=3Ddate><DFN>Date</DFN>: Mon Jun 03 2002 - 17:55:20=20
EDT</SPAN><BR></ADDRESS>
<P>I thought this might be interesting to those of you who are designing =

PC-&gt;VGs. <BR>
<P>I'm at the point where I need to know how fast a VG must run to =
emulate all=20
the <BR>known X/Y games. <BR>
<P>Instead of knowing how fast the different monitors run, and running =
the VG at=20
<BR>that speed, I decided to try and figure out how fast the games =
actually ran.=20
<BR>
<P>This is the results, but first, some background: <BR>
<P>I started by picking a standard to describe the speed of a VG. I went =
with=20
<BR>microseconds per inch -- or How many microseconds does the vector =
generator=20
take <BR>to move the CRT trace 1" on a 19" monitor. Since different =
monitors use=20
<BR>different voltages, this rating allows all 19" monitors to be =
treated=20
equally. <BR>
<P>13", 15", and 25" are run with the same inputs as the 19" monitors, =
so a=20
trace <BR>on a 13" monitor will be moving slower, and on a 25" it will =
move=20
faster, but <BR>the VG will run at the same speed for all the monitors, =
so I=20
standardized on the <BR>19" monitor's "inch" for speed comparisons. <BR>
<P>Using a standard 19" tube, with a viewable 18" diagonal screen, gives =
a=20
viewable <BR>screen width of 14.5". All the VGs were symmetrical for X =
and Y, so=20
I only <BR>calculated X's speed. <BR>
<P>The DVGs were the easiest. They all use 10bit DACs and divide the =
screen into=20
<BR>1024x768 addressable positions. All that must be done is figure out =
the=20
clock <BR>rate of the counters going into the DAC to determine the speed =
of the=20
VG. <BR>
<P>For instance Asteroids requires 1023 steps of the DAC counter to draw =
a line=20
<BR>from one side of the monitor to the other, which is 14.5". The =
counters are=20
<BR>clocked at 1.5mhz, so it takes 682us to draw a 14.5" vector, or 47us =
to draw=20
a <BR>1" vector. <BR>
<P>AVGs were a bit more difficult to calculate. I had to determine the =
fastest=20
<BR>speed the integrator's capacitor could charge, based on the AM6012 =
specs,=20
then <BR>follow the voltages through gain stages to the outputs, then =
use these=20
voltages <BR>to determine how fast it would take to draw a vector from =
-8v to=20
+8v. This is <BR>the voltage change required on a WG or Amplifone draw a =
full=20
14.5" vector. <BR>
<P>The thing about AVGs is that their draw speeds are software =
selectable by=20
<BR>changing the scaling. So the numbers for the AVG are the maximum =
speeds the=20
AVG <BR>can be run, not necessarily the speed a particular game is =
actually=20
running. <BR>
<P>Also shown in the table is the Normalized Average vector speed. To =
actually=20
<BR>draw an angled vector at full speed would required a multiply and =
divide to=20
<BR>determine the ratio needed for the slower DACs value. <BR>
<P>Since these VGs did not have specialized MUL/DIV for vector ratio=20
calculations, <BR>they all used a normalization technique to determine =
the=20
vector drawing speeds. <BR>This uses simple shift and test logic, but =
vector=20
draw speeds can be nearly 100% <BR>slower using the shift logic, than a =
MUL/DIV=20
would allow. On the average, random <BR>vector angles, will be drawn 50% =
slower=20
than the VG would allow, given MUL/DIV <BR>abilities. But note: =
Horizontal,=20
Vertical and 45 degree angles are drawn at <BR>full speed, so any =
emulation must=20
be able to keep up with the maximum draw <BR>rates. <BR>
<P>Here's what I came up with, based on the schematics I have: <BR>
<P>DVGs: <BR>
<P>Game us/inch Normalized Avg DAC clock rate <BR>---- ------- =
--------------=20
-------------- <BR>Atari DVG 47us/inch, 70us/inch 1.5mhz <BR>Omega Race=20
47us/inch, 70us/inch 1.5mhz <BR>Sega DVG 27us/inch, 40us/inch 2.57mhz =
<BR>Cosmic=20
Chasm 24us/inch, 36us/inch 3.0mhz <BR>
<P>
<P>AVGs: <BR>
<P>Game us/inch Normalized Avg <BR>---- ------- -------------- =
<BR>Tempest=20
51us/inch, 76us/inch <BR>Star Wars 6.3us/inch, 9.4us/inch <BR>
<P>
<P>A couple of interesting things I noticed, if you compare the above =
speeds=20
with <BR>monitor speeds at <A=20
href=3D"http://www.arcademonitors.com/vector_slew_rates.html">http://www.=
arcademonitors.com/vector_slew_rates.html</A>.=20
<BR>
<P>First you see that the Sega DVG runs at just about the limit of what =
a WG=20
6100 <BR>monitor is capable of. This explains why you can almost play =
the Sega=20
games on <BR>a WG monitors. The monitor is capable of keeping up with =
the=20
fastest drawn <BR>vectors (barely), but probably is not capable of =
keeping up=20
with the high speed <BR>jumps between vector draws. <BR>
<P>Second, the Star Wars vector generator is able to draw vectors faster =
than=20
any <BR>of the listed monitors! So software has obviously slowed down =
the vector=20
draw <BR>speeds, but to what speeds I don't know. It would take hooks in =
an=20
emulator, or <BR>an analysis of the disassembled code to determine what =
speeds=20
Star Wars uses to <BR>draw its vectors. Future work... <BR>
<P>Note that for a DVG to keep up with the Star Wars AVG you would have =
to clock=20
<BR>its DACs at 11.19mhz!! You can see one of the reasons Atari went to =
an=20
Analog <BR>VG! <BR>
<P>For our VG we've used a jumper to change between two different draw =
speeds,=20
<BR>depending upon the vector monitor being run, the above calculations =
were to=20
<BR>determine what those speeds should be. <BR>
<P>I have the luxury of having MUL and DIV instructions, so I can run =
all=20
vectors <BR>at full speed (no normalization problems). <BR>
<P>Right now it looks like if I had a slow speed setting of 27us/inch =
for WG=20
<BR>monitors, I would be able to emulate all Sega games on a WG monitor. =
Since I=20
<BR>can run all vectors at 27us/inch, and many of the Sega vectors =
average=20
around <BR>40us per inch, I will have extra time between the vectors to =
allow=20
the WG <BR>monitor to make it to the start of a new vector before =
drawing, and=20
still get <BR>all the vectors drawn during the allocated refresh rate. =
<BR>
<P>By having a high speed setting of 10us/inch, for high speed monitors=20
<BR>(Amplifones, 6401, G05, Sega?), I should be able to emulate all =
current=20
vector <BR>games. <BR>
<P>I can always change these speeds through experimentation, but you =
have to=20
start <BR>somewhere. <BR>
<P>I hope this helps all those others who are also designing PC-&gt;VGs! =
<BR>
<P>-Zonn=20
